 for bestpractices and # User Management (Admin)

## Overview
Build a complete Admin User Management feature for Archject that enables platform and studio administrators to view and manage studio user accounts, invite new users with role assignment, perform bulk actions (suspend/reactivate/resend invite/change role), and audit all administrative actions. This feature must integrate into the Admin Dashboard and Admin Tools & Analytics and follow the provided visual style and UX guidelines. Provide frontend pages, components, backend APIs, database schemas, security rules, validations, and acceptance criteria so an AI development tool or full-stack team can implement end-to-end.

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- The "User Management (Admin)" page is the primary administrative console for managing users across a studio (and for enterprise-level admins, across multiple studios). It provides a searchable, sortable user table, invite workflow, bulk action capability, per-user detail panel, and an audit trail (administrative actions log). It sits inside the Admin Dashboard and is connected to Admin Tools & Analytics for usage/health metrics and enterprise management workflows.

Goals:
- Give admins rapid visibility into all studio users, their roles, last activity, and account status.
- Enable safe, auditable user lifecycle actions: invite, resend invite, suspend, reactivate, remove, and change roles.
- Provide bulk operations for efficiency while requiring appropriate confirmations and audit logging.
- Maintain a complete, queryable audit trail of admin actions for compliance and dispute resolution.
- Surface relevant analytics (counts by role/status, recent sign-ins, suspended accounts) and connect to support tickets where user-reported issues appear.

Connected features:
- Admin Tools & Analytics: usage metrics (active users, invites sent, suspensions), health/performance alerts, enterprise-level user management.
- Admin Dashboard: navigation, global search, tenant selection (for enterprise), support tickets integration (link to related tickets), and CSV export.
- Authentication & Roles system used across Archject.

UI elements & visual guidance:
- Page layout: left permanent sidebar (Admin navigation), top bar, main content area with a primary card containing a search/header row and user table.
- Header area card contains: page title (H1), subtitle, "Invite user" primary button (#0052CC), "Bulk actions" dropdown, and summary chips (total users, active, suspended).
- Prominent full-width search bar with left search icon and filters: role dropdown, status (active/pending/suspended), last login range, invited date range, and sort selector (name, last login, role).
- User table: columns — checkbox, avatar, full name (link to user detail), email, role (badge/pill), studio(s) (if enterprise), last login (relative time + exact tooltip), status (badge: Active #10B981, Pending/Invited #F59E42, Suspended #EF4444), created date, actions (three-dot menu: view, impersonate (enterprise only), change role, resend invite, suspend/reactivate, remove).
- Row interactions: hover lift, click name to open a right-side slide-over "User detail" card with editable fields and activity timeline.
- Invite flow: modal with email(s) input (support comma/newline), role assignment dropdown, optional message, expiration (optional), send button; inline validation and preview of invite email; success toast and audit log entry. For bulk invites, allow CSV upload.
- Bulk actions: suspend/reactivate/resend invite/change role/remove — with multi-select and a confirmation modal showing affected users and required justification field (for audit).
- Audit Trail: card or tab showing admin actions table with filters (admin, action type, date range, target user, studio), export CSV, and show per-entry details (timestamp, admin id/email, IP, reason).
- Analytics mini-panel: small cards or sparkline charts showing monthly active users, weekly invites, suspensions, average last-login recency — pulled from Admin Tools & Analytics API.
- Support Tickets link: each user detail has a link to open related support tickets in Admin Dashboard.
- Accessibility: keyboard navigation across table, screen-reader friendly labels, focus outlines.

API integrations:
- No external APIs mandated; define internal REST/GraphQL endpoints for user CRUD, invites, bulk operations, audit logs, and analytics. Provide hooks for Admin Tools & Analytics to fetch metrics. All actions must create audit records.

## Components to Build
- AdminUserManagementPage (container)
- UserSearchBar with filter panel
- UsersTable component with row actions and multi-select
- UserRow component (avatar, name link, badges)
- UserDetailSlideOver (read/edit user, activity timeline, support tickets link)
- InviteUserModal (single & bulk with CSV upload)
- BulkActionConfirmModal (with justification input)
- AdminActionsMenu (per-row actions)
- AuditTrailView (table, filters, export)
- AnalyticsCards (small KPIs & charts)
- StatusBadge, RolePill components
- Toast/Notification system integration
- Frontend client service for API calls (userService)
- Backend controllers/handlers for users, invites, bulk actions, audit logs
- Database tables/models: users, invites, admin_actions (audit), roles, user_roles, studios, studio_users, support_tickets (reference), analytics aggregates
- Background job worker for sending invite emails and processing CSV invites
- Unit and integration test suites for frontend and backend

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Framework: React (preferred) + TypeScript. Use component-first approach (atomic components).
- State management: React Query for server state, context for UI state (selected studio/tenant).
- Styling: Tailwind CSS or design system tokens matching provided Visual Style (colors, typography). Use 12-column responsive grid.
- Responsive behavior: Desktop primary; table stacks into cards on mobile with key info (name/email/role/status), actions accessible via overflow menu.
- Accessibility: ARIA attributes for modals, slide-over, table rows, and buttons; keyboard shortcuts for search focus and bulk action confirmation.
- Components & interactions:
  - UsersTable: server-side pagination, server-side sorting & filtering. Each row has checkbox for selection. Sticky header and quick-select all.
  - Sorting: clickable column headers with ascending/descending indicator.
  - Per-row actions: three-dot menu with aria-label for each action.
  - InviteUserModal: validate emails, show duplicates, allow role selection, studio assignment (if enterprise), optional expiry days. Show preview of invite.
  - UserDetailSlideOver: edit displayName, role selector (role change must trigger backend audit), view last login, list of recent sessions, link to support tickets, button to "Impersonate" (if allowed).
  - BulkActionConfirmModal: list of selected users (max 100 preview, warn if >100), reason text area (required), confirm button disabled until reason present. Show potential consequences (e.g., suspending revokes tokens).
  - AuditTrailView: paginated with filters and per-entry expand to see JSON payload.
  - AnalyticsCards: call analytics endpoint to show KPIs; charts optional (sparklines).
- Client-side validation rules per "Validation" section.

### Backend
- Language/Framework: Node.js + TypeScript (Express or Fastify) OR a GraphQL server—specify REST endpoints below. Use ORM (Prisma/TypeORM/Sequelize) — Prisma preferred.
- Auth: integrate with existing auth provider (JWT or session). Ensure endpoints require admin role; enterprise/tenant-scoped authorization checks.
- APIs:
  - GET /admin/users — list users with pagination, filters, sort (studioId optional)
  - GET /admin/users/:id — user detail
  - POST /admin/users/invite — send invites (single/bulk); queue emails
  - POST /admin/users/invite/upload — CSV processing endpoint
  - PATCH /admin/users/:id — update user fields (role, name)
  - POST /admin/users/bulk — bulk action endpoint {action, userIds, payload} (suspend/reactivate/resend/changeRole/remove)
  - POST /admin/users/:id/suspend and /reactivate (or use PATCH with status)
  - POST /admin/users/:id/impersonate — create limited-time token (enterprise-only)
  - GET /admin/audit — list admin actions with filters
  - POST /admin/audit — internal endpoint used to record actions (or a DB trigger)
  - GET /admin/analytics/users — kpi endpoints aggregated
  - GET /admin/users/:id/support-tickets — list linked support tickets
- Background Jobs:
  - invite-email worker: send transactional invite emails, handle bounces, retries, and mark invite records.
  - CSV invite processor: parse, validate, create invite records, enqueue emails, and produce report.
- Audit logging:
  - All admin actions must write to admin_actions table: action_type, admin_id, admin_email, target_user_id, target_user_email, studio_id, timestamp, ip_address, reason (optional), payload (json).
  - For critical changes (suspend, remove, change role, invite), write full before/after snapshot (hashed for privacy if needed).
- Data retention and export: audit logs exportable as CSV/JSON via GET /admin/audit?export=csv.
- Tests: backend unit tests for endpoints and audit logging; integration tests for invite flow and bulk actions.

### Integration
- Frontend uses React Query to call backend endpoints; optimistic UI for role changes but revert on failure and show error toast.
- All admin actions call backend and await confirmation; backend writes audit record and returns updated user list or status.
- Background worker posts status updates to a notification system or Event store; frontend polls or subscribes to job status via websocket for large CSV invites.
- Admin Tools & Analytics pull aggregated metrics from analytics endpoints; ensure analytics DB (or materialized views) updated by background jobs/cron.

## User Experience Flow
1. Admin navigates to Admin Dashboard → User Management (Admin).
2. Page loads with summary KPIs (total users, active, suspended, invited) and searchable users table (first page).
3. Admin uses search bar and filters (role/status/studio/date range); table updates via server-side queries.
4. Single-user flow:
   - Click a user name → slide-over opens showing full profile, last login, sessions, roles, actions.
   - Admin edits role → chooses new role from dropdown → confirms change → backend updates user and writes audit record → UI shows success toast and audit entry appears in Audit Trail.
   - Admin suspends user via actions menu → confirmation modal asks for reason (required) → on confirm, backend suspends account, revokes tokens, logs audit, UI updates status badge.
5. Invite flow:
   - Click "Invite user" → modal opens → enter one or multiple emails, select role and studio (if enterprise), add message → validate.
   - Submit → validator catches duplicates/invalid emails → backend creates invite records, enqueues emails → success toast with link to export invites or view report.
6. Bulk flow:
   - Select multiple users with checkboxes → click "Bulk actions" dropdown → select "Suspend users" → BulkActionConfirmModal shows users list and requires reason → confirmed → backend applies changes, logs audit entries, returns summary. If >100 users, backend returns job id; frontend shows job progress.
7. Audit Trail:
   - Admin opens "Audit" tab, filters for last 30 days, searches for actions on a user, and exports CSV.
8. Analytics:
   - Admin views small charts and KPI cards; clicks a KPI to filter users table (e.g., suspended users).
9. Support Tickets:
   - From user detail, click "View support tickets" → open tickets panel in Admin Dashboard.

## Technical Specifications

- Data Models:

1) users
- id: uuid (PK)
- email: string (unique, indexed)
- display_name: string
- avatar_url: string | null
- status: enum('active','invited','suspended','deleted')
- created_at: timestamp
- updated_at: timestamp
- last_login_at: timestamp | null
- login_count: int
- metadata: jsonb (optional)

2) roles
- id: uuid
- name: string (e.g., Admin, Editor, Reviewer, Viewer)
- permissions: jsonb

3) user_roles
- id: uuid
- user_id: uuid (FK)
- role_id: uuid (FK)
- studio_id: uuid (FK) — nullable for platform-level roles
- assigned_by: uuid
- assigned_at: timestamp

4) studios
- id: uuid
- name: string
- enterprise_id: uuid | null

5) studio_users
- id: uuid
- studio_id: uuid (FK)
- user_id: uuid (FK)
- role_id: uuid (FK)
- joined_at: timestamp
- status: enum('active','suspended','invited')

6) invites
- id: uuid
- email: string
- inviter_id: uuid
- role_id: uuid
- studio_id: uuid | null
- token: string (secure random)
- expires_at: timestamp | null
- status: enum('pending','sent','accepted','expired','failed')
- created_at: timestamp
- sent_at: timestamp | null
- metadata: jsonb

7) admin_actions (audit)
- id: uuid
- admin_id: uuid
- admin_email: string
- action_type: string (e.g., 'INVITE_CREATE','USER_SUSPEND','ROLE_CHANGE','BULK_SUSPEND')
- target_user_id: uuid | null
- target_user_email: string | null
- studio_id: uuid | null
- timestamp: timestamp
- ip_address: string | null
- reason: text | null
- payload: jsonb (before/after snapshots)

8) support_tickets (reference)
- id, user_id, studio_id, subject, status, created_at, link_to_ticketing_system

9) analytics_user_metrics (materialized or aggregated)
- date, active_users_count, invites_sent, suspensions_count, avg_last_login_days

- API Endpoints (REST style, all under /admin):
1) GET /admin/users
- Query params: page, perPage, q, role, status, studioId, sortBy, sortDir, lastLoginFrom, lastLoginTo
- Response: { data: User[], total, page, perPage }

2) GET /admin/users/:id
- Response: detailed user object, roles, studios, sessions summary

3) POST /admin/users/invite
- Body: { emails: string[], roleId, studioId?, message?, expiresInDays? }
- Response: { invitesCreated: [{email, inviteId, status}], warnings: [] }

4) POST /admin/users/invite/upload
- Form-data: file (CSV), roleId, studioId?
- Response: { jobId }

5) PATCH /admin/users/:id
- Body: { displayName?, roleId?, status? } — role/status changes must include reason in header or separate body field when coming from admin

6) POST /admin/users/bulk
- Body: { action: 'suspend'|'reactivate'|'resend_invite'|'change_role'|'remove', userIds: uuid[], payload?: {roleId?}, reason: string }
- Response: { jobId | results }

7) GET /admin/audit
- Query params: page, perPage, adminId, actionType, targetUserId, studioId, from, to, export=csv
- Response: paginated audit entries or CSV attachment

8) GET /admin/analytics/users
- Query params: range=30d|90d|365d
- Response: { kpis, series }

9) POST /admin/users/:id/impersonate
- Body: { ttlSeconds? }
- Response: { token, expiresAt }

10) GET /admin/users/:id/support-tickets

- Security:
  - Authentication: All endpoints require a valid admin JWT/session.
  - Authorization: RBAC checks:
    - Platform super-admins can manage across all studios.
    - Studio admins can manage users scoped to their studio only.
    - Enterprise admins can manage all studios in enterprise (tenant scoping).
  - Impersonation: Only allowed for platform/enterprise admins and must be logged as an audit action; token limited in scope and time.
  - Rate-limiting: Invitations and bulk actions guarded to prevent abuse (e.g., max invites per minute, bulk limit with job pattern).
  - Sensitive data: Audit payloads must be stored securely with access controls; PII handling policy for logs.

- Validation:
  - Emails: RFC5322-compliant validation; block disposable email domains (optional).
  - Role IDs: Must be valid and allowed for the admin (can't assign higher privilege than own).
  - Bulk operations: Require reason string (min 10 chars) and must limit number of immediate sync operations (if >threshold, return job).
  - Invite CSV: columns: email, role (optional), studio (optional). Reject file if >5000 rows in single upload — require chunking.
  - User update: Display name length 2..100 chars. Avatar URL validated as URL.
  - Pagination: perPage capped to 100.

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Admin can view paginated list of users with search, sorting, and filters (role/status/studio) and accurate result counts.
- [ ] Admin can open user detail slide-over and view/edit allowable fields; role changes persist and appear immediately.
- [ ] Admin can send single and bulk invites with validation; invite emails are queued and invite records created; duplicates handled gracefully.
- [ ] Admin can perform bulk suspend/reactivate/change-role/remove actions; actions require confirmation and reason and produce audit records; large jobs run asynchronously with job tracking.
- [ ] All admin actions (invite, suspend, role change, impersonation) create entries in admin_actions with admin identity, timestamp, IP, reason, and payload.
- [ ] Audit Trail is searchable and exportable (CSV).
- [ ] Analytics cards display KPIs and clicking a KPI can filter the users table appropriately.
- [ ] Authorization enforcement prevents non-admins from accessing endpoints and ensures studio-scoped admins cannot manage outside their studio.
- [ ] UI follows provided Visual Style, is responsive, accessible (keyboard & screen reader), and has tests for core user flows.

## UI/UX Guidelines
Apply the project's design system:
- Use the specified color palette and typography sizes.
- Cards are white with subtle shadow and rounded corners.
- Buttons: primary = #0052CC with white text, secondary ghost for less emphasis.
- Status badges use #10B981 (active), #F59E42 (pending/invited), #EF4444 (suspended).
- Inputs: rounded edges, border #D1D5DB, focus ring subtle.
- Table: sticky header, thin dividers (#E5E7EB), hover background #F3F4F6.
- Sidebar and top bar follow the provided navigation design; active section uses accent highlight.

---

Notes for implementer:
- Prioritize server-side pagination/filters for large orgs.
- Build audit logging as an independent service or DB table so it’s non-blocking for user-facing operations; however, synchronous audit of critical actions (role change, suspend) is required before returning success to frontend.
- Provide feature flags for enterprise-only features (impersonation, cross-studio management).
- Keep invite email templates configurable (branding & message).
- Include telemetry for actions (counts, latencies) to Admin Tools & Analytics.

Deliverables:
- Frontend code (React+TypeScript) for all components, pages, modals, and tests.
- Backend code (Node.js+TypeScript) with described endpoints, database models (Prisma schema or equivalent), background job workers, and tests.
- Postman/Swagger or GraphQL schema documenting APIs.
- Deployment notes describing necessary env variables (email provider, job queue, feature flags), database migrations, and permissions.

